08/10/2004
BUCHAREST, Romania -- The World Bank has approved a $225m credit earmarked for infrastructure construction, according to an announcement by the transport ministry Thursday (7 October). 
Most of it would be used by the National Motorway and National Road Corporation to build segments of the national road system. 
The remaining $75m would be used for railway restructuring.
In other news, two members of the panel investigating records of the secret police quit Thursday, after controversial findings were announced. 
Andrei Plesu and Mircea Dinescu resigned after the commission concluded that Corneliu Vadim Tudor, a popular presidential candidate and associate of the late dictator Nicolae Ceausescu, had no link to the secret police. 
